                                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Are Kobalt Power Tools at Lowe's Worth Buying?]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/are-kobalt-power-tools-at-lowes-worth-buying/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Cory Gunther]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/set-of-kobalt-power-tools-displayed-on-a-blue-background.png" length="1283" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Hobbies]]></category><category><![CDATA[tools]]></category><category><![CDATA[Home improvement and maintenance]]></category><category><![CDATA[DIY]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            What DIYers need to know about Lowe's power tool line. 
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>When you need a new power tool and wander into any big-box hardware store, you'll see all sorts of options on the shelves. Power tools come in various styles, brands, and price points. Do you own any of the blue Kobalt tools from Lowe's? Here's where Kobalt tools are made and whether they're worth buying.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 14:15:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/are-kobalt-power-tools-at-lowes-worth-buying/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[The Best Streaming Services for Asian Dramas, K-Pop, and More]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/the-best-streaming-services-for-asian-dramas-k-pop-and-more/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[T.M. Amrita]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/streaming.png" length="2434" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Streaming]]></category><category><![CDATA[Netflix]]></category><category><![CDATA[Tubi]]></category><category><![CDATA[Amazon Prime Video]]></category><category><![CDATA[Apple TV+]]></category><category><![CDATA[YouTube]]></category><category><![CDATA[Video Streaming]]></category><category><![CDATA[Rakuten Viki]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Know where to find your favorite Asian content on streaming services. 
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Are you slowly getting into <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/best-movies-and-shows-for-fans-of-k-pop/" target="_blank">K-pop, K-dramas</a>, and related entertainment niches, but don't know where to find content? Mainstream streaming platforms may host content in many languages, but not all of them have a sizable catalog of Asian titles.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 14:00:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/the-best-streaming-services-for-asian-dramas-k-pop-and-more/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[AdGuard Now Works Much Better on Tablets]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/adguard-now-works-much-better-on-tablets/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Jorge A. Aguilar]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/agnar-the-adguard-mascot-in-front-of-a-green-gradient-radial-background.jpg" length="121" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Android]]></category><category><![CDATA[Android Phones & Tablets]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Another helpful update.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>AdGuard for Android has just rolled out version 4.12. There will finally be proper landscape mode support. If you're one of the many who use AdGuard on a tablet, you can now expect a much more convenient experience when holding your device horizontally.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 14:00:02 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/adguard-now-works-much-better-on-tablets/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[How Android Battery Stats Lie]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/how-android-battery-stats-lie/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Faisal Rasool]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/illustration-of-an-android-mascot-next-to-a-nearly-empty-battery-icon-labeled-full-with-a-time-estimate-above.png" length="718" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Android]]></category><category><![CDATA[Android Phones & Tablets]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            The many ways Android guesses the battery status, and why it's never precise.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>We assume that when the little battery icon in our phone's status bar says "44%", it means the battery has 44% charge left. Pretty simple, right? I no longer believe that, and the reasons why will probably change your mind, too.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 13:30:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/how-android-battery-stats-lie/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[How to List Linux Services With systemctl]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/839285/how-to-list-linux-services-with-systemctl/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Dave McKay]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2025/09/52849124270_37375d86a3_o.jpg" length="145" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Linux]]></category><category><![CDATA[Linux & macOS Terminal]]></category><category><![CDATA[Servers]]></category><category><![CDATA[Homelab]]></category><category><![CDATA[Ubuntu]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Get the inside scoop on services and daemons.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Your Linux computer relies on a lot of background tasks called services or daemons. On systemd-based distributions you have built-in commands that let you see which services are running, disabled, or failed.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 13:15:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/839285/how-to-list-linux-services-with-systemctl/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[5 Smartphones That Are Thinner Than the iPhone Air]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/smartphones-that-are-thinner-than-the-iphone-air/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Goran Damnjanovic]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/rumored-iphone-17-air-displayed-with-a-gradient-background-and-curved-lines.png" length="2858" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Android]]></category><category><![CDATA[Android Phones & Tablets]]></category><category><![CDATA[Apple iPhone Air]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            The iPhone Air isn't as thin as you think. 
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Apple touts the iPhone Air as one of the thinnest phones ever, which is technically true, if we choose to ignore that massive camera bump. Without it, the iPhone Air has a depth of only 5.6mm, making it the slimmest iPhone ever. But it's far from the thinnest phone out there.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 12:30:17 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/smartphones-that-are-thinner-than-the-iphone-air/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[8 Practical Uses for the Python os Module]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/practical-uses-for-python-os-module/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Zunaid Ali]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/python-logo-over-blurred-python-code-background-with-the-word-python-written-in-yellow-underneath.png" length="2949" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Programming]]></category><category><![CDATA[Python]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Building the bridge between Python and your operating system.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Worried about creating operating system independent programs in Python? The <code data-end="980" data-start="976">os</code> module is Python's direct line to your operating system. Think of it as the Swiss Army knife for everyday tasks related to your system. Let’s see what tricks the <code data-end="980" data-start="976">os</code> module has up its sleeve.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 12:00:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/practical-uses-for-python-os-module/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[How I Built a Cheap Alarm System With Home Assistant and Some Sensors]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/i-made-a-cheap-security-alarm-system-with-home-assistant-and-some-sensors/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Tim Brookes]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/ikea-parasoll-sensors-being-unboxed.jpg" length="6818" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Smart Home]]></category><category><![CDATA[Home Assistant]]></category><category><![CDATA[Home Security]]></category><category><![CDATA[automation]]></category><category><![CDATA[Apple HomeKit & Apple HomePod]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Because nothing says "home security" like "built it myself."
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Home security systems are expensive and often come with ongoing costs, but smart home technology has never been more affordable or accessible. Though pricey alarm systems still have their place, I figured I could use sensors and automations to throw something together on the cheap.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 11:00:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/i-made-a-cheap-security-alarm-system-with-home-assistant-and-some-sensors/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Want to See Some Meteors? The Orionid Meteor Shower Is Happening Now]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/orionid-meteor-shower-2025/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Tony Phillips]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/a-meteor-shower-with-some-mountains-in-the-background.jpg" length="924" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Space]]></category><category><![CDATA[Astronomy]]></category><category><![CDATA[Stargazing]]></category><category><![CDATA[science]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Quick! Head outside!
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>We're into October, which means that the Orionid meteor shower—one of the few astronomical displays that can be reliably observed in both hemispheres—is happening right now. It offers many bright, fast meteors with long-lasting trains, so you won't want to miss it.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 10:30:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/orionid-meteor-shower-2025/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Home Assistant Finally Lets You Undo and Redo in Automations]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/home-assistant-finally-lets-you-undo-and-redo-changes/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Jorge A. Aguilar]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/home-assistant-logo.jpg" length="125" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Smart Home]]></category><category><![CDATA[Home Assistant]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            You're getting shortcut keys to do it quickly, too.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Home Assistant has officially dropped its October release. Home Assistant 2025.10 is bringing some massive quality-of-life improvements to the Automation editor, along with smarter dashboards and even the ability for your connected AI model to generate images.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Wed, 01 Oct 2025 21:05:19 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/home-assistant-finally-lets-you-undo-and-redo-changes/</guid></item></channel>
